<subSubSection pageId="51" pageNumber="52" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="51.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,692,717]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Comments:</emphasis>
The species 
<taxonomicName box="[491,721,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="procne">
<emphasis box="[491,721,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Allometopon procne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[738,836,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 315 – 320. 315, 316" captionStartId="122.[151,264,1820,1843]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetId="figure@122.[151,1436,193,1799]" captionTargetPageId="122" captionText="FIGURES 315 – 320. 315, 316. Allometopon procne spec. nov., holotype, photos; 315: dorsal; 316: lateral. 317, 318. A. tetrathrix spec. nov., holotype, photos; 317: dorsal; 318: lateral. 319, 320. A. trimaculosum Sasakawa, holotype, photos; 319: dorsal; 320: lateral." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258818/files/figure.png" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">
Fig. 
<number box="[793,836,692,717]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" value="315.0">315</number>
</figureCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName box="[904,1050,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philomela">
<emphasis box="[904,1050,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">A. philomela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are geographically isolated sister species characterized by an apical brown spot on the halter, a brown U-shaped marking on the frons and the posterolateral corner of the frons lateral to the vertical setae, thickened stripes on the back of the head, a spot on the proepisternum and prosternum, a partially brownish face, a yellow tergite 
<number box="[978,994,799,824]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" value="6.0">6</number>
, and yellow sublateral bands on at least tergites 
<number box="[240,254,836,860]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" value="4.0">4</number>
and 
<number box="[309,325,836,861]" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" value="5.0">5</number>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[337,565,836,861]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="procne">
<emphasis box="[337,565,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">Allometopon procne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be most readily diagnosed by an entirely brown notum and palpus, while 
<taxonomicName box="[151,293,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="51" pageNumber="52" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philomela">
<emphasis box="[151,293,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="51" pageNumber="52">A. philomela</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a wide medial yellow stripe on the scutum that continues onto the scutellum and mediotergite, and a palpus that is only brown apically.
</paragraph>
